The English translation of "Lateinamerika im Kampf gegen das Coronavirus" is:  "Latin America in the fight against the Coronavirus"
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented size and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not meet the crisis with decisiveness, it could become the tragically worst episode in Latin American history.
So far, the political reactions in our region have been very diverse.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health to be their top priority.
On the other hand, some downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, provided their citizens with false information, and not only ignored scientific research but also disregarded the advice of their own experts.
These state leaders chose a populist and divisive policy amidst the tragedy.
The first priority for Latin America must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
The politicians must focus on improving health systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily utilizing idle infrastructure such as hotels or convention centers, and significantly increasing testing capacities.
Moreover, Latin American states must reject export controls on medical supplies and other vital resources and advocate for additional resources for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in stark contrast to US President Donald Trump’s ruthless decision to freeze around $500 million in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacities, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – in order to ultimately end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only was Latin American domestic production interrupted, but the countries there also suffer from declining export volumes and prices, income losses due to absent tourism and fewer foreign remittances, as well as significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could trigger a contractionary spiral together with the collapse of demand.
To prevent this, bold measures are necessary to protect household incomes.
This means transferring support to the crisis victims, including informal and independent workers who do not have access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief measures for companies are important as well.
Subventions, which help companies pay their wages and payroll expenses, protect both the companies and their employees during the crisis. Thus, they are crucial for a swift economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of insolvencies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And then at this point, the payment system — and with it the entire national economy — is endangered.
Many companies, particularly small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the shortage of liquidity will soon turn into a solvency problem.
Tax breaks, payment delays, and subsidized loans will not be sufficient.
This emergency requires not only unprecedented government credit guarantees to ensure that banks continue to lend, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and managed state banks can play a leading role in this.
From a broader perspective, while measures may differ from country to country, it is likely that extraordinary budget resources will be necessary overall to accelerate the recovery.
The governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without worsening the health risks.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America today is even narrower than it was after the global financial crisis of 2008.
Thus, the budget burdens must be offset by adjustments in areas of lower priority.
The risk of a downgrade of creditworthiness is present, but this can be mitigated by governments' promise to correct higher budget deficits within an appropriate timeframe.
However, external support for budgets and balance of payments is urgently needed, in particular for the smaller and less developed Latin American countries.
If both private companies and states incur higher deficits, the performance balances of the countries will likely worsen as well.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the greatest reversals in the modern history of financial markets – exacerbate the problem even further.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing influence.
In many of the region's economies, the only way to cope with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to receive much more external support.
Here, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a crucial role.
He must address the short-term currency and budgetary needs of the countries and continue to support the economies of those that are facing an uncertainty in duration during this crisis.
For this, he needs more resources and the ability to pay them out quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a new edition of the global reserve currency of the IMF – special drawing rights that should amount to one billion Special Drawing Rights (SZR).
Although the SZR is assigned to member countries based on their IWF quotas, a non-proportional allocation could be achieved by establishing a common pool under the supervision of the fund.
Additionally, the IMF could create the necessary capacity through an immediate doubling of the volume of New Credit Arrangements to meet the expected strong credit demand.
And finally, the fund must improve access to low-threshold tools with quick disbursements – such as its Rapid Financing Instrument – or introduce new credit facilities for the pandemic, since traditional IMF credit programs are not being approved in a timely manner.
Large central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps – either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the Bank for International Settlements, which can extend liquidity to central banks.
In the inland areas, central banks must utilize all available instruments and, if necessary, create new ones to supply financial markets and the economy with sufficient liquidity.
And finally, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursements in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets to be able to provide additional budget support.
In exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official credit provision could be supplemented by a debt haircut.
The MEB should also provide guidelines to the countries regarding the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – particularly for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
In this process, time plays a decisive role.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is without precedent in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean regions cannot afford delayed or inadequate reactions.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reasonableness remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagogy.
The crisis must not be used as an excuse to weaken our hard-won citizen's rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and demonstrate what it can offer to its citizens.
